Assumption Parish Sheriff's Office
September 2 at 3:16 PM ¬∑

To all houseboat/large boating vessel owners:Due to recent mechanical issues with the Pierre Part Bay bridge ,if you will need to pass through the bridge as the Labor Day weekend approaches,we urge you to do so before 12 noon of whichever day you choose to leave.If you do not do so, there are no guarantees that the bridge tender will be able to open for you.Same for your return trip.The problem is a heat related issue that DOTD is working to correct.We thank you for your patience.

According to Advisory 28, pictured, it shows us right now in the area of experiencing tropical storm force winds which at this time are not yet currently happening. Radar depicted a tornado in the Paincourtville area earlier this afternoon. We have no reports of it touching down or specific tornadic damage reported at this time.

Stay alert and aware.

Tropical Storm LAURA Update
There‚Äôs been no shift to the projections on Tropical Storm Laura as of the 4pm National Weather Service Update. Currently, forecasts show landfall late Wednesday in the Lake Charles/Cameron area as a Category 2 hurricane with sustained winds of 105 mph. These projections show our area feeling tropical storm force winds at around 3:00 pm on Wednesday. *BIG FACTOR HERE IS there is lots of time for this forecast to change as Laura makes its way into the Gulf. Do not let your guard down as Marco fades. Stay alert and prepared.

post_text:
Tropical Storm LAURA Update
All eyes are on Laura as the storm makes its way into the Gulf of Mexico. The track is moving NW and the system is expected to reach Category 2 status before landfall late Wednesday/early Thursday of this week. While the track forecast hasn't changed much since yesterday evening, we remain extremely vigilant watching Laura. Our offices are in constant communication with the National Weather Service and state and other local agencies regarding potential hazardous weather this week.

post_text:
Tropical Storm MARCO Update
Attached is the 10:00 a.m. advisory which shows a forecast shift and further weakening of Marco. The system is projected to pass over Assumption parish; however, it is expected that we will receive less than 2" rainfall and winds shouldn't reach tropical storm force speed. At this time, there will be no parish shelter opened for this storm. While there are no sand sites throughout the parish (due to the rain forecast and low water levels), there is sand available for self-bagging at the Parish Barn (from 7am-5pm) located at 141 Hwy 1008 in Napoleonville (bags provided/bring your own shovel).

All parish Police Jury offices are open with normal business hours. Waste Management has advised that they plan to resume regular service on tomorrow.

post_text:
Tropical Storm MARCO Update
The 4:00 pm advisory shows Marco tracking a little more west which is a better situation for Assumption parish; however, as we have seen over the last couple of days‚Ä¶ all forecasts are subject to change. Stay aware.

*At this time, based on rainfall forecasts due to Marco along with locally lower water levels, there are no sand sites open. We will re-evaluate early tomorrow once NWS advisories are available.
*Waste Management has suspended services on tomorrow and they plan to resume normal service on Tuesday pending weather conditions. We will keep you updated on any changes.
*There is no information available for open shelters in the parish at this time. This will be addressed on tomorrow along with early morning advisories.
*Entergy is concentrating on manpower for power restoral should we experience any interruptions in service. They are prepared to work as soon as weather conditions allow.

post_text:
TROPICAL STORM MARCO
Parish officials met via conference call a little while ago regarding Marco's latest track. The storm is currently projected to be Cat 1 when making landfall in the Grand Isle area with the eye over Assumption parish at approximately 11:00 p.m. tomorrow night. Of course we know forecasts change - this is the current advisory so always be alert to forecast changes. We will meet again after the 4:00 p.m. update from the National Hurricane Center and more information will be forthcoming. Today is the day to secure your homes and businesses and prepare for several days of potential hazardous weather conditions.

Assumption Parish Waterworks District No.1
August 11 at 1:28 PM ¬∑

Beginning around 9:00 AM, Assumption Parish Waterworks will be repairing a mail line leak at 2779 Highway 1, Labadieville, LA ON August 11, 2020. Water will be off at the following locations: from 2729 Hwy 1 at Oak St. to 2971 Hwy 1 at Parkers Motel, Sevin Court, Palm Lane, Dogwood Street, Sycamore Street, Birch Street, Poplar Street, Locust Road and Oak Street. This water outage will affect about 95 customers living on the streets listed. Water will be turned off around 9:00AM to 12:00PM (approximately 3 hours). We will lift the boil water advisory once the bacteriological samples are received and are found to be in compliance from the State of Louisiana‚Äôs Lab. Please pass the message to family and friends in the affected areas. We appreciate your patience and cooperation regarding this matter.

post_text:
From NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE-NOLA:
Overview

WHAT: MARGINAL RISK of Severe Weather

MARGINAL RISK to SLIGHT RISK of Excessive Rainfall that could lead to localized flooding issues

WHEN: Today and tonight

WHERE: Slight risk of excessive rainfall for areas west of Baton Rouge. Marginal risk of excessive rainfall for the rest of the area. Marginal risk of severe weather for all of SE LA and S MS.

Impacts:

The main threats associated with any severe storms will be:

¬∑ Wind gusts up to 60 mph which could down trees and powerlines and/or cause structural damage

¬∑ Isolated tornadoes - a few of which could be strong

In addition to the severe weather threat, rainfall of 1 to 3 inches will be possible. Locally heavy rainfall could lead to ponding of water in low lying areas and areas of poor drainage.

post_text:
Amid the ongoing public health crisis, Louisiana has been approved for the new Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) program. This program will provide extra help buying groceries for the families of the more than 600,000 children who normally receive free and reduced-price meals at school. Eligible families who complete an online application will be issued a P-EBT debit card by the Louisiana Department of Children and Family Services (DCFS) to access benefits. The P-EBT card will function like a standard EBT card, and the same guidelines will apply. Families will receive $285 in total P-EBT benefits per child. Unused benefits will roll over month to month and must be used within 365 days.

TO VIEW FLYER: https://www.louisianabelieves.com/docs/default-source/covid-19-resources/louisiana-p-ebt-information-and-application.pdf?fbclid=IwAR2YUKizZSyy4xM2IB3crrM5Px8Jkh6gmPRbz4BDKYCp3rui5-gZ7JgYp6U

TO APPLY: https://pebt.doe.louisiana.gov/PublicApps/SNP/offline

post_text:
Police Jury President Jeff Naquin, all Jurors, Sheriff Falcon, OEP Director John Boudreaux and other parish officials just got off of a conference call discussing the latest forecast of TS Cristobal. It is a better forecast for our area than what we were preparing for on yesterday. The track has shifted a little more to the east.

The Emergency Shelter did open this morning at Napoleonville MIddle School and will remain open as long as folks are checked in. It is a shelter of last resort and all who enter must bring their own bedding, food, drink, medications and any other necessary personal items. (No pets or alcohol allowed.)

Entergy was also on the call and advised that they are prepped and ready with contractors on standby to address any potential power outages that could be associated with this tropical system.

Our Emergency Operations Center is active and staffed and constantly watching and advising of all weather forecasts.

When: Opens Sunday, June 7, 2020 @ 8:00 a.m.

**FILLED SANDBAG PICK-UP SITE**
In preparation for Tropical Storm Cristobal and through the cooperation and assistance of the Assumption Parish Sheriff's Office, filled sandbags are available at the Ag Center (119 Robin St/Napoleonville) while supplies last. Please be prepared to load your truck/trailer without assistance at this site.

To avoid any type of traffic congestion and in adherence to promoting social distancing guidelines, we ask that once you enter Robin Street from LA-308 to please drive through the back of the open air pavilion to your right (where the sandbags are located). Once loaded, you can easily exit out of the pavilion onto Robin Street.

post_text:
From NWS NOLA:

Overview:

WHAT: MARGINAL RISK to SLIGHT RISK of Excessive Rainfall
WHEN: Today
WHERE: across most of southeast LA, southwestern Ms and coastal MS.
CONFIDENCE: Low in the coverage of rain however, confidence is a little higher that a line of storms will develop over the area. The biggest question is where that may occur. If it is east of I-55. The line itself may be very slow to move east while the individual storms move to the northeast which would lead to some locations seeing multiple storms that could lead to rain quickly adding up and with rainfall totals well above current forecast. There is a chance that many locations west of where this line develops could see little if any rain.

Impacts:
The main threats associated with any severe storms will be:
¬∑ rainfall of 0.5 to 1.5 inches will be possible. Locally heavy rainfall could lead to ponding of water in low lying areas and areas of poor drainage.
¬∑ Isolated flash flooding possible especially if any locations receive multiple rounds of rain and received heavy rain a few days ago.

Governor John Bel Edwards
May 14 at 11:32 PM ¬∑

Louisiana will enter into Phase One on Friday, May 15, when the Stay at Home order will be lifted and more businesses will open with strict social distancing, enhanced sanitation and required masks for employees helping the public.

Louisianans should still stay at home as much as possible to avoid unnecessary exposure to COVID-19. People who are at a higher risk of severe illness from COVID-19 should still stay at home unless they are traveling outside of the home for an essential activity.

Thanks to the hard work of the people of Louisiana under the Stay at Home order, we have seen declining new COVID-19 cases & hospitalizations. This, coupled with increased testing and contact tracing capacity, is what is allowing us to move to Phase One on Friday.

This is not mission accomplished or a victory against COVID-19, but it is a positive and hopeful move for Louisiana. #lagov

In response to the COVID-19 public health emergency, businesses were required to close or restrict activity to preserve and protect the health and safety of the citizens of Louisiana. Because of the success of these efforts, Louisiana is now ready to move forward with opening businesses in a safe, phased-in approach.

Visit: https://opensafely.la.gov/

This site allows you to register your business and your registration allows you to receive updated communication, notifications, and helpful guidance via email from the State Fire Marshal‚Äôs Office specific to your business type. These notifications will answer the important questions:

When can I partially or fully open my business?

What are the steps to open my business?

What changes can be expected for businesses that have been operating, but with restrictions?

What restrictions are my business subject to, if any?

Are there any new sanitation requirements for my business?

Are there any personal protective requirements (masks, gloves, etc.) for my employees?

Assumption Parish Sheriff's Office
May 6 at 3:55 PM ¬∑

This coming weekend ,the weather forecasts are very good, hence , we anticipate significant boating traffic on the waterways of our parish .We ask that you comply with the "NO WAKE ZONES".

For the past couple of weeks, we have received complaint's of trash being dumped into our beautiful waterways and along it's banks.Our patrol vessels have encountered used gloves,face masks ,and now common materials used during the COVID 19 crisis as well as beer containers,food wrappers,etc.Please bring a trash bag with you on your excursion and correctly dispose of these items when you return home.

The Marine Division will be enforcing the above!

We thank you for your cooperation!

Through the coordination of the Assumption Parish Office of Homeland Security & Emergency Preparedness and the Police Jury and with cooperation from the Sheriff‚Äôs Office and Louisiana National Guard, 800 boxes of dry food groceries and produce were distributed at the Community Center in Napoleonville.

As of this morning, the boat launch in Lower Texas has been cleaned and is now trash free. Let‚Äôs all do our part in keeping it that way! Please take your trash home with you coming or leaving the launch to ensure that your trash will not be left behind to spread around this beautiful launch! Your cooperation and willingness to help keep this area clean for all to enjoy is greatly appreciated. Please remember to idle leaving the launch to protect the land on both sides of the bayou until you reach 500 ft. If this does not eliminate the problem then we will ask the Assumption Parish Sheriff‚Äôs Office and Wildlife and Fisheries to get involved. Thank you in advance for helping to keep Lower Texas boat launch and bayou sides clean.

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
April 22 at 11:08 PM ¬∑

Part of our new normal will mean wearing a mask or face-covering in public. Wearing a mask in public is just like holding a door open for someone, it's being kind and courteous, and it will be critical to Louisiana moving forward.

When I say mask, I mean wearing some sort of cloth facial covering. We've seen creative folks make masks out of t-shirts or other household materials, and I am encouraging everyone to begin the process now to start getting them for yourselves and your families.

Take this time to make sure you and everyone in your family has a face covering, you can buy or make masks. Remember, unless you are a healthcare worker, you do not need to wear or purchase N95 or surgical masks. #lagov #MaskUpLa

post_text:
Contrary to behavior we might be seeing all around us, the STAY HOME order is still in place. It has not changed. In all likelihood, it may be extended. It is extremely important that we continue to adhere to the orders in place as COVID-19 numbers continue to rise right here at home, across the state, and nationally.

We have advised before that the LDH numbers released at noon each day are not instantaneous reporting. We know our number here in Assumption is higher than that report because of constant communication with regional agencies as well as inter-agency communication right here at home.

*The count we have this morning is up to 139 cases and very sadly, 4 deaths.*

We know it's hard to do. We all feel it. As we enter this weekend, we ask you to please stay home and only leave or interact with others outside of your home if it's absolutely necessary.
